Poweranalysis

CK

24/08/2020

The data set

The data consists of measurements of 36 pasture-soil samples (0－10cm) which are historically contaminated with dieldrin residues. Dieldrin is extremely persistent and therefore still found in the surface soil after three decades of natural attenuation.

The samples were taken in 12 paddocks in two different soils, with three field replicates at representative areas of each paddock. So overall the data consists of:

  • 2 soils
    • 12 paddocks (7 + 5)
      • 36 samples (3 per paddock, 21 + 15)

Total dieldrin loss (%) since 24-30 years was recorded per paddock. Thus, dieldrin residue concentrations (µg/g soil) and other soil measurements were measured for all samples (n = 36) but dieldrin loss (%) was available per paddock only (n = 12).

Power analysis

Questions:
- From the available 36 samples (21 for soil 1 and 15 for soil 2), how much power does a suitable test have to determine if there are significant differences between the two soils? If I understand power correctly, then it is the chance of getting a significant results i.e. power = percent(<=0.05).
- How many samples are needed per sample to get the true mean of dieldrin concentrations?
- How many paddocks are needed to model biological data to dieldrin loss?

Some reading
- Statistical power analysis: A simple and general model for traditional and modern hypothesis tests (Murphy, Myors, and Wolach 2014)
- Statistical Power Analysis (Cohen 1992)

pwr package

The following is based on the pwr package vignette:
https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/pwr/vignettes/pwr-vignette.html

t-test

How powerful is this experiment if we want to detect a “large” effect in either direction with a significance level of 0.05

# Effect size large = 0.8

pwr.t.test(n = 15, d = 0.8, sig.level = 0.05)
## 
##      Two-sample t test power calculation 
## 
##               n = 15
##               d = 0.8
##       sig.level = 0.05
##           power = 0.5617849
##     alternative = two.sided
## 
## NOTE: n is number in *each* group
pwr.t.test( d = 0.8, sig.level = 0.05, power = 0.8)
## 
##      Two-sample t test power calculation 
## 
##               n = 25.52458
##               d = 0.8
##       sig.level = 0.05
##           power = 0.8
##     alternative = two.sided
## 
## NOTE: n is number in *each* group

Result:
The sample size is uneven between the two soils (n= 21, n = 15) so the t-test is not suitable. However, doing it anyway and using the lower number of n (n = 15) and a large effect size (how do we actually calculate d for t-tests as 0 -1?), the power of a t-test would be relatively low (power = 0.56).

If we wanted to redo this experiment (using equal sample sizes) 25 samples per soil are needed to test for significant differences at a power of 0.8.


F-test

# Calculate the number of samples needed to model Dlossmean (12 samples) with CN as predictor
# https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/pwr/vignettes/pwr-vignette.html
# The effect size is the R2 of the model. the coefficient of determination, aka the “proportion of variance explained”
pwr.f2.test(u = 1, f2 = 0.5/(1 - 0.5), sig.level = 0.001, power = 0.8)
## 
##      Multiple regression power calculation 
## 
##               u = 1
##               v = 20.6584
##              f2 = 1
##       sig.level = 0.001
##           power = 0.8
#n = v + u + 1
# n = 21 + 1 + 1 = 22 paddocks needed at an effec size of 0.5


Do resampling of mean dieldrin concentrations

Calculate the power of getting the true mean of dieldrin concentrations from the pilot (n = 36). Resample 1000x across both soils and calculate mean and std of dieldrin concentrations.

# Notes 

#calc mean and std 1000 x
# calc distr. of means and std
# variation from the mean
# sample size less 30 - t distribution
# look up the table
# simulations

resample = 1000
measurement = 'D1517'

# The mean mean function
meanfunction <- function(df){
df %>% rstatix::get_summary_stats(measurement, type = "mean_sd")  
}

# Function to randomly resample the mean 1000x with replacement and get a df with the mean of each resample
# Do this once as this takes time and do not repeat for histogram
listfunction <- function(df){
listdf <- replicate(resample, dplyr::slice_sample(df, n= n, replace = TRUE), simplify = FALSE) %>%
  lapply(., meanfunction) %>% 
  bind_rows  
return(listdf)
}

# Function to get a summary statistic of the mean
summaryfunction <- function(listdf){
  listdf %>% rstatix::get_summary_stats(mean, type = "common")
}


# Function to get a historgram of the means
histofunction <- function(summarydf){
plotting <- summaryfunction(summarydf)
  summarydf %>% ggpubr::gghistogram(x= "mean", title = paste(resample,"x resampled with n =", n, ", mean =", plotting$mean, "stdv =", plotting$sd))
}

Lets say we take the mean and SD from the resampling with n = 10 and calculate the chance that the mean was outside the 2 SDs (outside of 95% of all probabilities). In other words, assuming the distribution was normal, how often does the mean fall outside the 95% of the resampled mean population?

So of the 1000 resamples calculate the percentage of times that the mean values are above 2xSD and below 2xSD. In other words how many times to we get P( (X < (µ - 2SD)) + (X > (µ - 2SD)) ) = 0.05

mean( (summarydf %>% dplyr::select(mean)) > (summarydf %>% dplyr::select(mean) + 2*summaryfunction(summarydf)$sd) )
## [1] 0
mean( (summarydf %>% dplyr::select(mean)) < (summarydf %>% dplyr::select(mean) - 2*summaryfunction(summarydf)$sd) )
## [1] 0

Result:
Never! 2*SD is always higher or lower then the sampled means. Need to understand this.. ongoing


A robust mean?

The following is based on http://r-video-tutorial.blogspot.com/2017/07/power-analysis-and-sample-size.html
Using: \[N = {2 * SD \choose SE}^2\] This is approximately at 95% confidence where N is the number of samples, SD the standard deviation and SE is the standard error. These values can be obtained from previous experiments, or from the literature

## # A tibble: 2 x 6
##   Soil      variable     n   mean    sd    se
##   <fct>     <chr>    <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 Kurosol   logD1517    21 -0.866 0.282 0.061
## 2 Chromosol logD1517    15 -0.021 0.179 0.046
## [1] "Based on this simplified formula to compute the minimum number of samples (see link) 85 samples are needed for the Kurosol and 61 samples are needed for the Chromosol"

Result:
At a fixed 95% confidence the Kurosol requires more samples as the SE is lower in this soil. So despite that the values in the Chromosol are more variable, less samples are apparently required. Thus one can be 95% confident that the values are more variable in the Chromosol and fall between a wider value range x1…xn ? If so, then it does not seem appropriate to use this simplified calculation which uses the standard error and another method is needed.

Here the same formula is applied to dieldrin losses (n= 12):

# n = ((2 x STD) / SE )^2
data <- metadata2 %>% group_by(Paddock) %>% summarise(Dlossmean = mean(Dloss), CNmean = mean(CN))
sum_stat <- data %>% rstatix::get_summary_stats(Dlossmean, show = c("mean", "sd", "se"))
n = ( (2 * sum_stat$sd) / sum_stat$se )^2
# n = 48 samples needed for the mean dieldrin loss  to be robust
n 
## [1] 48.00781

Accordingly, 48 samples were needed for the mean dieldrin loss to be robust

Confidence intervals (bootstrapped)

# Get bootstrapped confidence interval for dieldrin concentrations per sample.
rcompanion::groupwiseMean(D1517 ~ 1, data = metadata2, conf = 0.95, digits = 3,
                          boot = TRUE, R = 1000)
##    .id  n  Mean Boot.mean Conf.level Trad.lower Trad.upper
## 1 <NA> 36 0.524     0.523       0.95      0.343      0.705
# Get bootstrapped confidence interval per soil
rcompanion::groupwiseMean(D1517 ~ Soil, data = metadata2, conf = 0.95, digits = 3,
                          boot = TRUE, R = 1000)
##        Soil  n  Mean Boot.mean Conf.level Trad.lower Trad.upper
## 1   Kurosol 21 0.158     0.159       0.95      0.126       0.19
## 2 Chromosol 15 1.040     1.040       0.95      0.775       1.30
# Group data by paddock and select dieldrin loss - n = 12
meandata <- metadata2 %>% group_by(Soil, Paddock) %>% summarise(Dlossmean = mean(Dloss))
meandata %>% group_by(Soil) %>% get_summary_stats(Dlossmean, type = "mean_se")
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   Soil      variable      n  mean    se
##   <fct>     <chr>     <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 Kurosol   Dlossmean     7  73.1  2.81
## 2 Chromosol Dlossmean     5  42    6.40
# Test normality of dieldrin loss n = 12
shapiro.test(meandata$Dlossmean)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  meandata$Dlossmean

# Get bootstrapped confidence interval of dieldrin loss per paddock
rcompanion::groupwiseMean(Dlossmean ~ 1, data = meandata, conf = 0.95, digits = 3,
              boot = TRUE, R = 1000)
##    .id  n Mean Boot.mean Conf.level Trad.lower Trad.upper
## 1 <NA> 12 60.2      60.3       0.95       48.1       72.2
